<subSubSection id="4986433DE1F10611014DED77EEA71E32" pageId="0" pageNumber="22175" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="FEF72FCFA53C947D1E71530DF9FABC10" pageId="0" pageNumber="22175">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph id="265EA92A3C2B1506D7218DA59522B9BE" pageId="0" pageNumber="22175">
Males of 
<taxonomicName id="0C9D275ECDE8159B76054FCA7AB05DE8" genus="A." lsidName="A. vernalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="22175" rank="species" species="vernalis">A. vernalis</taxonomicName>
are distinguished from congeners by several morphological characters, including the structure of the male genitalia (Fig. 10; see also 
<bibRefCitation id="A8122BB39873D7BC126E6D814FDC8BCB" author="Chandler, P. J." journalOrPublisher="Brill, Leiden-Boston-Koeln" pageId="0" pageNumber="22175" title="The flat-footed flies (Diptera: Opetiidae and Platypezidae) of Europe. Fauna Entomologica Scandinavica" year="2001">Chandler (2001)</bibRefCitation>
, Fig. 107-109), while females are recognised by peculiar abdominal marking (
<bibRefCitation id="0F74D3AD888207D3290E936883CDF8F3" author="Chandler, P. J." journalOrPublisher="Brill, Leiden-Boston-Koeln" pageId="0" pageNumber="22175" title="The flat-footed flies (Diptera: Opetiidae and Platypezidae) of Europe. Fauna Entomologica Scandinavica" year="2001">Chandler 2001</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 110, 111).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1728E77373B2E94BF778C7B561D94650" pageId="0" pageNumber="22175" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="129EE7BBCBBF15A151209729A1C577EB" pageId="0" pageNumber="22175">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B3B6D2205C5DC0A13BDEAB2947DF3899" pageId="0" pageNumber="22175">
